In this document we will analyze if there is a relation between the odds and matches results. Then we will focus on how we can compress images using PCA.

Data Preperation

Below you can see the codes thatwas used in the previous homework to prepare the data. Details of the code was clarified in the previous homework.

Task 1-2 A

This task is to understand if we can obtain significant information regarding the game outcomes using the odd data from multiple bookmakers.

Final odds from the odd data is obtained. And in this homework only final odds for each bookmaker will be used. Unfortunately each bookmaker does not offer an odd for each betType/oddType. This is why in the PCA data we shoud deal with the NA values.

Deleting each match that has an NA value is an option. But this would lead to a huge data loss. This is why I believe replacing NA values is a better option. But at this point the replacement method become very important. Any wrong replacements may causes wrong results.

Any NA odd value for a bookmaker can be replaced with the help of the other bookmakers’ odd offers. In order to choose the replacement values in a better way I firstly classify the bookmakers. I created clusters consists of bookmakers that have relatively close odd offers.

From below you can see the use of kmeans function in order to cluster the bookmakers. the steps that are followed can be seen from below :

  1. Bookmakers are clustered with respect to their 1x2 type Odd1 offers. So firstly the filtering is done.
  2. In this type of offer for each match there are maximum 27 bookmakers that offer an odd.
  3. Matches that has odds from 27 bookmakers are selected.
  4. With the kmeans function Clusters are obtained.
GameRes=FinalOdds[betType=="1x2" & oddtype=="odd1" ][,c("bookmaker","matchId","odd")]
GameRes[,count:=.N,matchId]

unique(GameRes$bookmaker)

MatchesForCluster=unique(GameRes[count==27]$matchId)
GameRes2=GameRes[matchId %in% MatchesForCluster][order(-odd)]

GameRes3=dcast(GameRes2, bookmaker~matchId,value.var="odd")

GameRes=na.omit(GameRes)

Cluster=kmeans(GameRes3[,c(2:359),with=F],4)
BookmakerClusters=as.data.table(cbind(GameRes3$bookmaker,Cluster$cluster))

After clustering bookmakers, as it is asked in the hw 5 Bookmakers are selected as it is done in the previous homework. Top 5 bookmakers that has the most odds offers are selected. In order to answer the question about the relation between the odss and the Game Results(Home,Away,Tie / Over-Under 2.5) the match results are obtained for both bettypes.

MatchesCleaned[,OUResult:=as.numeric(ScoreSum>2.5) ]
MatchesCleaned=MatchesCleaned[ScoreHome>ScoreAway,GameResult:= 1 ]
MatchesCleaned=MatchesCleaned[ScoreAway>ScoreHome,GameResult:= 2 ]
MatchesCleaned=MatchesCleaned[ScoreAway==ScoreHome,GameResult:= 0 ]

Firstly bet365 bookmaker is chosen. Then the data is reshaped with the dcast function so that PCA can be applied.After dcast function we obtain the NA values. In order to replace the NA values the data is melted again. With the new data containing the NA values replacement is done according to the bookmakers that are in the same cluster with Bet365. After replacement the normalization is applied to the features so that we would not be affected from the odd ranges for different types of odds.

Data2=Data[bookmaker=='bet365']
Data2$bookmaker=NULL

setnames(BookmakerClusters,'V1','bookmaker')

setnames(BookmakerClusters,'V2','Cluster')

setkey (FinalOdds,bookmaker)
setkey (BookmakerClusters,bookmaker)


NAReplacements=BookmakerClusters[FinalOdds][,Type:=paste0(betType,"_",oddtype,"_",totalhandicap)]
NAReplacements=NAReplacements[,list(Mean=mean(odd)),list(Type,Cluster)]

setkey(NAReplacements,Type,Cluster)

ShapedData=dcast(Data2,matchId ~   Type ,value.var="odd")

DataMelted =melt(ShapedData)
## Warning in melt.data.table(ShapedData): To be consistent with reshape2's
## melt, id.vars and measure.vars are internally guessed when both are 'NULL'.
## All non-numeric/integer/logical type columns are considered id.vars, which

## or 'measure' vars in future.
NewOdds=NAReplacements[Cluster== BookmakerClusters[bookmaker=='bet365']$Cluster]

setkey(NewOdds,Type)
setkey(DataMelted,variable)

NewOdds2=NewOdds[DataMelted][is.na(value),value:=Mean]

NewOdds2[,Max:=max(value),Type]
NewOdds2[,NormalizedOdd:=(value-Min)/(Max-Min) ]
NewOdds2[Max==Min,NormalizedOdd:=1 ]

As you can see from the below plots for the over/under 2.5 game result can not be explained by the odds for different types of bets. We can not see a pattern that can help us to conclude that o/u 2.5 results can be ecplained by the odds.

But for the 1X2 et Type we can say that there is a pattern in the related plot. This means that the Game result (Home/Awat/Tie) can be explained by the odds.

Task 1B

For this task we follow the same strategy by applying multidimensional scaling (MDS). Since we are given a data matrix. We need to transform this information to distance matrix.

Firstly distance matrix is calculated with the dist function for both Manhattan and Eucledian distances.Then these distances are given to the cmdscale function as input. You can see the related code part below.

EucDistance=dist(ShapedDataTaskB[,c(4:109),with=F],diag=T,upper = T)
ManhattanDistance=dist(ShapedDataTaskB[,c(4:109),with=F],method="manhattan")

mds=cmdscale(EucDistance)
mdsManhattan=cmdscale(ManhattanDistance)

The distance between the matches are calculated based on the odds offerred. From below We can see that the 1x2 BetType can be explaned with the odds clearly. The pattern can be seen as it is in PCA.

There is a difference between the Mannathan distance plots and Eucledian distance plots. The conclusion is that in the eucledian distances the plots are much more scattered. In the Mannathan distance plots the points are much more closer to each other. we may conclude that we may loose information in manhattan distance compared to the eucledian distance.

Task 3

In this task, you are requested to perform certain operations on images. The aim is to compress images using PCA.

I took a picture of Harry Potter books, then resize it to 512x512.

Step 1: The image is read with the readJPEG function as can be seen from below.

image=readJPEG("C:/Users/eda/Downloads/imagee.jpg", native = FALSE)

Step 2: The structure of the picture stored is a number array with the dimensions [1:512, 1:512, 1:3] the structure is obtained with the help of the code:

str(image)
##  num [1:512, 1:512, 1:3] 0.608 0.612 0.624 0.62 0.624 ...

a.Displaying the Image with the code

plot(0:5+0.5, 0:5+0.5, type="n",ANN=FALSE,axes = FALSE)

b.Display each channel

par(mfrow=c(3,1)) 

r <- image(image[,,1])
g <-image(image[,,2])
b <- image(image[,,3])

  1. Creating Noisy Image

I use runif function to generate genarate uniformly distrubited random numbers between 0 and 0.1 for each channel, z1,z2,z3.

Then I create a sparse array having the same sizes with the real image and add the random numbers to the real pixel values to create noisy image.Then I capped the values with maximum 1 since the images stores numbers between 0 and 1.

z1=runif(512*512, min=0, max=0.1) 
z2=runif(512*512, min=0, max=0.1) 
z3=runif(512*512, min=0, max=0.1) 


imageNoised <- array(rep(0, 512*512*3), c(512, 512, 3))

imageNoised[,,1]=image[,,1]+matrix(unlist(z1), ncol = 512, byrow = TRUE)
imageNoised[,,2]=image[,,2]+matrix(unlist(z2), ncol = 512, byrow = TRUE)
imageNoised[,,3]=image[,,3]+matrix(unlist(z3), ncol = 512, byrow = TRUE)

A=imageNoised[,,1]
A[A>1]=rep(1,length(A[A>1]) )
B=imageNoised[,,2]
B[B>1]=rep(1,length(B[B>1]) )
C=imageNoised[,,3]
C[C>1]=rep(1,length(C[C>1]) )

imageNoised[,,1]=A
imageNoised[,,2]=B
imageNoised[,,3]=C

Noisy image can be seen from below:
